, "prob": 0.8986574411392212, "span": {"begin": 1849, "end": 1864}}, {"id": ["mesh:C518919"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CHIR", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9978411197662354, "span": {"begin": 1911, "end": 1915}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001688"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "BIO", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9794889688491821, "span": {"begin": 1920, "end": 1923}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "primary transcripts", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.8084838390350342, "span": {"begin": 1972, "end": 1991}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:442912"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "miR-302-367 cluster", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9013795256614685, "span": {"begin": 1999, "end": 2018}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miR", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8987358808517456, "span": {"begin": 2023, "end": 2026}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:406954"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "miR-181 family", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9015548229217529, "span": {"begin": 2023, "end": 2037}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7471"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Wnt", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9860824346542358, "span": {"begin": 2064, "end": 2067}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1499"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "beta-catenin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9742606282234192, "span": {"begin": 2068, "end": 2080}}, {"id": ["mesh:C417521"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SB216763", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988346695899963, "span": {"begin": 2114, "end": 2122}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2932"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSK3beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935484528541565, "span": {"begin": 2132, "end": 2140}}, {"id": ["mesh:C547688"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TWS119", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.995884358882904, "span": {"begin": 2165, "end": 2171}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2932"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSK3beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9936714172363281, "span": {"begin": 2181, "end": 2189}}, {"id": ["mesh:C473710"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CHIR98014", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9772509932518005, "span": {"begin": 2212, "end": 2221}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2932"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSK3beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9807721376419067, "span": {"begin": 2231, "end": 2239}}], "text": "The protein encoded by gsk3b gene is a serine-threonine kinase belonging to the glycogen synthase kinase subfamily. It is a negative regulator of glucose homeostasis and is involved in energy metabolism, inflammation, ER-stress, mitochondrial dysfunction, and apoptotic pathways. Defects in this gene have been associated with Parkinson disease and Alzheimer disease (GSK3B Gene - GeneCards). GSK3b has been identified within mitochondria (Hoshi et al., 1996), as well as in the cytoplasm (Anichtchik et al., 2008).  GSK3b kinase is constitutively active in resting cells and undergoes a rapid and transient inhibition in response to a number of external signals. GSK3b activity is regulated by site-specific phosphorylation. Full activity of GSK3b generally requires phosphorylation at tyrosine 216 (Tyr216), and conversely, phosphorylation at serine 9 (Ser9) inhibits GSK3b activity. Phosphorylation of Ser9 is the most common and important regulatory mechanism. Many kinases are capable of phosphorylating Ser9, including p70 S6 kinase, extracellular signal-regulated kinases (ERKs), p90Rsk (also called MAP-KAP kinase-1), protein kinase B (also called Akt), certain isoforms of protein kinase C (PKC) and cyclic AMP-dependent protein kinase (protein kinase A, PKA). In opposition to the inhibitory modulation of GSK3b that occurs by serine phosphorylation, tyrosine phosphorylation of GSK3b increases&nbsp; the&nbsp; enzyme&rsquo;s&nbsp; activity (Grimes and Jope, 2001; Luo, 2012).  Glycogen synthase kinase 3beta (GSK3 beta) is inhibited by CHIR99021 (C. H. Li et al., 2017; C. C. Liu et al., 2016; Sineva &amp; Pospelov, 2010).  Glycogen synthase kinase 3beta (GSK3 beta) is inhibited by BIO (6-bromoindirubin-3&rsquo;-oxime) (Mohammed et al., 2016; Sineva &amp; Pospelov, 2010).  Kenpaullone is a dual inhibitor for GSK3 alpha/beta and HPK1/GCK-like kinase (Y. M. Yang et al., 2013; Yao et al., 1999).  CHIR and BIO treatments lead to a slight upregulation of the primary transcripts of the miR-302-367 cluster and miR-181 family of miRNAs, which activate Wnt/beta-catenin signaling (Y. Wu et al., 2015).  SB216763 inhibits GSK3beta (Naujok et al., 2014).  TWS119 inhibits GSK3beta (Tang et al., 2018).  CHIR98014 inhibits GSK3beta (Guerrero et al., 2014; Lian et al., 2014).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:53:34 +0000 2026"}